            <fr:title text="Convergent">Convergent</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_n)]]></fr:tex> in a metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is said to converge to a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x_n, x) < ε]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \geq  N]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In this case, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is called the limit of the sequence, and we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \to  x]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \to  \infty ]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n \to  \infty } x_n = x]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In functional analysis, there are various notions of convergence depending on the space and the context, including <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0034.xml" addr="FA-0034" title="Weak Convergence">weak convergence</fr:link>, <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0035">convergence in norm</fr:link>, and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0036.xml" addr="FA-0036" title="Pointwise Convergence">pointwise convergence</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
